The 2016 crash shattered the bones in Jeremy Wallaert’s right leg. For eight months, doctors attempted to save the leg, surgically installing rods and hardware into the leg and stabilizing it in an external fixation device. But the efforts failed. (Courtesy of Lauren Wallaert)

Jeremy Wallaert’s Harley-Davidson motorcycle was severely damaged in August 2016 when authorities say Maryann O’Quinn was speeding, veered into Wallaert and other motorcyclists and lost control of the vehicle, injuring four of the motorcyclists and killing O’Quinn’s 15-year-old daughter.

The Wallaerts have struggled to adapt to the physical and emotional struggles of each losing a leg after a 2016 crash. “To this day, we still feel like every vehicle around us will crash into us,” Lauren Wallaert says. At right is daughter Hailey, 6. (Courtesy of Wild Things Photography)
One of the hardest aspects of losing a leg is finding comfortable prosthetics. “We have many days when we can’t wear our prosthetics because it’s too painful,” Lauren Wallaert says.
